	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Actually, the rgb121 method works quite well even without the flicker. Just by alternating the green channel with the red/blue channels every scanline you can get a pretty colorful image. I tried one of the most colorful pictures I could think of, which is a Super Sentai team:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=3530" alt="liveman-original.png" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">liveman-original.png [ 132.11 KiB | Viewed 2310 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br />And here are the individual rgb121 frames generated from that picture:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=3531" alt="liveman-a.png" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">liveman-a.png [ 9.97 KiB | Viewed 2310 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=3532" alt="liveman-b.png" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">liveman-b.png [ 10.07 KiB | Viewed 2310 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br />In both pictures the colors of the rangers are represented accurately enough, so even without the flicker the results are pretty decent compared to approaches that use a single name table.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
